How lonely sits the city that was full of people! How like a widow has she become, she who was great among the nations! She who was a princess among the provinces has become a slave.
<<<
Lamentations 1:1

<<<
I am the man who has seen affliction under the rod of his wrath;
<<<
Lamentations 3:1

The book of Lamentations is not just a raw venting of emotions but also a disciplined book. Even Jesus was a man of sorrows, well acquainted with grief. Hence why journaling is a great way to remove sorrow. (Not entirely sure about this part.)

Wormwood was a medicinal pain. Jeremiah is expressing at the bitterness of life.

2 Corinthians - Paul talking paradox of sorrow as a Christian.

You can learn a lot from sorrow versus the walk with pleasure. (i.e going to a funeral vs parties Ecclesiastes.)

!! Remember of God

<<<
But this I call to mind, and therefore I have hope:
<<<
Lamentations 3:21

Here Jeremiah is calling God to mind. Jeremiah's hope is what he chose to do with his mind. Hope is a result that a constant position that the believers make. It is a constant decision to fix one's eyes from the character of God.

Despair and constant discouragement is a result from being undisciplined. It is not being able to gird up your mind. Gird your loins.

Learn to put the Words, "but God" at the end of every conversations. "This circumstance looks difficult but God is faithful." "My heart is broken and all the day but God is my comforter, He is my helper."

The term hessid in Hebrew is almost untranslatable in the Hebrew language. Love, faithfulness, kindness, goodness. King James translates it as loving kindness.

Exodus 34:6; Hosea 2:16; Psalm 63:3

